### [Matthew Chapter 8](../../../bib/kjv/mat008.htm#001.md)

[Matthew 8:2](../../../bib/kjv/mat008.htm#002.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_002">mat 8:2</span></span>

behold, there came a leper

The King, having in Chapters 5-7. declared the principles of the
kingdom, makes proof, in Chapters 8, 9, of His power to banish from the
earth the consequences of sin, and to control the elements of nature.

Lord

Greek, "Kurios". The first occurrence of the word is applied to Jesus
with His evident sanction. In itself the word means "master," and is so
used of mere human relationships in, for example ([Mat
6:24](../../../bib/kjv/mat006.htm#024).md); ([Mat
15:27](../../../bib/kjv/mat015.htm#027).md); ([Mar
13:35](../../../bib/kjv/mar013.htm#035).md); ([Eph
6:9](../../../bib/kjv/eph006.htm#009).md) Both uses, divine and human, are
brought together in ([Col 4:1](../../../bib/kjv/col004.htm#001).md). It is
the Greek equivalent of the Hebrew, "Adonai."

(See Scofield) - ([Gen 15:2](../../../bib/kjv/gen015.htm#002).md),

and is so used by Jesus Christ in ([Mat
22:43-35](../../../bib/kjv/mat022.htm#043).md). In the New Testament the
distinctive uses of "Kurios" (Lord) are:

\(1\) As the New Testament translation of the Hebrew, "Jehovah" (Lord),
for example ([Mat 1:20](../../../bib/kjv/mat001.htm#020).md); ([Mat
1:22](../../../bib/kjv/mat001.htm#022).md); ([Mat
2:15](../../../bib/kjv/mat002.htm#015).md); ([Mat
3:3](../../../bib/kjv/mat003.htm#003).md); ([Mat
4:7](../../../bib/kjv/mat004.htm#007).md); ([Mat
4:10](../../../bib/kjv/mat004.htm#010).md); ([Mat
11:25](../../../bib/kjv/mat011.htm#025).md); ([Mat
21:9](../../../bib/kjv/mat021.htm#009).md); ([Mar
12:29-30](../../../bib/kjv/mar012.htm#029).md); ([Luk
1:68](../../../bib/kjv/luk001.htm#068).md); ([Luk
2:9](../../../bib/kjv/luk002.htm#009).md).

\(2\) Jesus Himself so uses "Kurios", for example ([Mat
4:7](../../../bib/kjv/mat004.htm#007).md); ([Mat
4:10](../../../bib/kjv/mat004.htm#010).md); ([Mat
11:25](../../../bib/kjv/mat011.htm#025).md); ([Mar
12:11](../../../bib/kjv/mar012.htm#011).md).

\(3\) But the great use of "Kurios" is as the divine title of Jesus, the
Christ. In this sense it occurs in the New Testament 663 times. That the
intent is to identify Jesus Christ with the Old Testament Deity is
evident from ([Mat 3:3](../../../bib/kjv/mat003.htm#003).md); ([Mat
12:8](../../../bib/kjv/mat012.htm#008).md); ([Mat
21:9](../../../bib/kjv/mat021.htm#009).md); ([Psa
118:26](../../../bib/kjv/psa118.htm#026).md); ([Mat
22:43-45](../../../bib/kjv/mat022.htm#043).md); ([Luk
1:43](../../../bib/kjv/luk001.htm#043).md); ([Joh
8:58](../../../bib/kjv/joh008.htm#058).md); ([Joh
14:8-10](../../../bib/kjv/joh014.htm#008).md); ([Joh
20:28](../../../bib/kjv/joh020.htm#028).md); ([Act
9:5](../../../bib/kjv/act009.htm#005).md); ([Act
13:33](../../../bib/kjv/act013.htm#033)). (Psalm 2.md).

